---
import '../styles/global.css';
import criteriaJson from '../../data/criteria.json';
import type { CriteriaFile } from '../../shared/src/schema';

const criteria = criteriaJson as unknown as CriteriaFile;
const SEAL_NAMES = ['No Sovereignty', 'Jurisdictional Sovereignty', 'Data Sovereignty', 'Digital Resilience', 'Full Digital Sovereignty'];
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>Methodology — Cloud Sovereignty Index</title>
</head>
<body class="bg-white text-gray-900 min-h-screen">
  <header class="border-b border-gray-200 px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between">
    <a href="/" class="font-semibold text-lg tracking-tight">Cloud Sovereignty Index</a>
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-600">
      <a href="/methodology/decisions" class="hover:text-gray-900">Decisions Register</a>
    </nav>
  </header>
  <main class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Methodology</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mb-10">Instrument v{criteria.instrument_version}</p>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">1. Overview</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        The Cloud Sovereignty Index (CSI) is a structured self-assessment instrument for evaluating the
        sovereignty posture of cloud services. It is based on the EU Cloud Sovereignty Framework (EU-CSF) v1.2.1
        and BSI Criteria Enabling Cloud Computing Autonomy (C3A) v1.0.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">2. Objectives & Weights</h2>
      <div class="space-y-2">
        {criteria.objectives.map(obj => (
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 py-2 border-b border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-14 font-mono text-xs text-gray-400">{obj.id}</div>
            <div class="flex-1 text-sm font-medium">{obj.title}</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-gray-500">{Math.round(obj.weight * 100)}%</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">3. SEAL / CSL Levels</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
        For EU/EEA assessments the metric is the <strong>SEAL</strong> (Sovereignty Effectiveness Assurance Level), as defined in EU-CSF §3.
        For non-EU (Generalized) assessments the equivalent metric is the <strong>CSL</strong> (Cloud Sovereignty Level).
        Both use identical methodology and the same 0–4 scale — only the label differs to avoid implying EU procurement compliance for non-EU organisations.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        {criteria.seal_levels.map(sl => (
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0"
              style={{ backgroundColor: ['#dc2626','#f97316','#eab308','#22c55e','#16a34a'][sl.level] }}>
              {sl.level}
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="text-sm font-medium mb-0.5">{sl.name}</div>
              <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">
                <span class="font-medium text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wide text-[10px]">SEAL (EU/EEA): </span>{sl.description}
              </div>
              {sl.description_generalized && (
                <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mt-0.5">
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wide text-[10px]">CSL (non-EU): </span>{sl.description_generalized}
                </div>
              )}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">4. Scoring</h2>
      <div class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Each question carries a point value and a sovereignty contribution level (1–4).</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>Yes</strong>: full points awarded, counts toward the sovereignty level</li>
          <li><strong>Partial</strong>: half points, does not count toward the sovereignty level</li>
          <li><strong>No</strong>: 0 points, does not count toward the sovereignty level</li>
          <li><strong>N/A</strong>: excluded from numerator and denominator</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The weighted score formula is: <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">Score = Σ (Score(SOVₙ) / MaxScore(SOVₙ)) × Weight(SOVₙ) × 100</code>
        </p>
        <p>
          Level per objective: the highest level L such that ALL criteria with contribution ≤ L
          are answered Yes (weakest-link rule, per EU CSF §4). Displayed as SEAL for EU/EEA
          assessments and CSL for Generalized (non-EU) assessments.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">5. Tiered Criteria & Country Adaptation</h2>
      <div class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          BSI C3A defines criteria at two levels: <strong>bloc-level (EU)</strong> and <strong>national-level
          (Germany in the source document)</strong>. The national tier is a strictly higher bar than the
          bloc tier — it applies to a specific member state rather than the EU as a whole.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Nesting rule:</strong> National tier ⊆ Bloc tier. A cloud provider that satisfies the
          national-level requirement (e.g., "data stored in France") automatically satisfies the
          bloc-level requirement ("data stored in the EU"). The reverse is not true.</p>

        <p><strong>Questionnaire flow for EU/EEA assessments with a country selected:</strong></p>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>The national tier question is shown first (e.g., "…stored in France").</li>
          <li>If the answer is <strong>Yes</strong> → the EU-level requirement is auto-satisfied. Only the national tier is scored; no further question is shown for that criterion.</li>
          <li>If the answer is <strong>No, Partial, or N/A</strong> → the EU-level (bloc) fallback question is shown immediately below. The respondent can still satisfy the EU-level requirement independently. Both tiers are scored at their respective levels.</li>
        </ol>

        <p><strong>Scoring of tiered criteria:</strong></p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>National = Yes</strong> → national tier points and sovereignty contribution counted; bloc tier auto-credited at the lower contribution level (no double-counting of points).</li>
          <li><strong>National = No/Partial, Bloc = Yes</strong> → bloc tier points and sovereignty contribution counted at the bloc level. National tier scored as answered (0 or half points).</li>
          <li><strong>Both = No</strong> → 0 points for both tiers.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Text substitution:</strong> Geographic placeholders are resolved at render time.
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">{"{{COUNTRY}}"}</code> → selected member state name (e.g., "France").
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">{"{{BLOC}}"}</code> → "EU" (EU-CSF variant) or the country name (Generalized variant).
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">{"{{NATIONAL_ADMIN}}"}</code> and
          <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">{"{{EMERGENCY_REGIME}}"}</code> → country-specific values from the methodology dataset.
        </p>

        <p>
          All adaptations and substitutions are documented in the{' '}
          <a href="/methodology/decisions" class="text-blue-600 underline">Decisions Register</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">6. Sources</h2>
      <div class="space-y-2">
        {criteria.source_documents.map(doc => (
          <div class="text-sm border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-3">
            <div class="font-medium">{doc.title}</div>
            <div class="text-gray-500 text-xs">{doc.publisher} · v{doc.version} · {doc.date}</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">7. Limitations</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        This is a self-assessment instrument, not a certification. Per C3A §1.1: "The C3A Framework
        is not binding in itself." The score is an indicative measure. Results depend on the accuracy
        and honesty of responses. No liability is accepted for decisions made based on assessment results.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</body>
</html>
